# Hearing Preparation Summary

Single document that orients counsel, frames issues, and provides a fast in-hearing reference.

## Prerequisites

1. Hearing notice or order with date, time, forum, and scope.
2. Operative pleadings and any amendments.
3. Key motions, briefs, and oppositions for the hearing.
4. Docket sheet and relevant prior orders or minute entries.
5. Evidence set: exhibits, declarations, discovery excerpts, transcripts.
6. Witness list with contact info and prior statements.
7. Applicable rules and authorities (statutes, rules, leading cases) or a request to research them.

## Output Structure / Process

Use this structure and fill every section that applies.

**1) Hearing Snapshot (table)**

| Field | Value |
| --- | --- |
| Hearing type |  |
| Date / time |  |
| Location / courtroom / link |  |
| Judge / officer / panel |  |
| Matter(s) set |  |
| Time limits |  |
| Burdens of proof |  |
| Applicable rules |  |

**2) Case Background (5-10 bullets)**  
Chronological, fact-only, with source citations.

**3) Procedural Posture (table)**

| Item | Date | Source | Impact |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Complaint / petition |  |  |  |
| Answer / response |  |  |  |
| Key motions / rulings |  |  |  |
| Pending issues |  |  |  |

**4) Issues Matrix (core section)**

| Issue | Standard | Moving party position | Opposing position | Key facts | Key authorities | Evidence tie-ins |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
|  |  |  |  |  |  |  |

**5) Legal Standards & Authorities (table)**  
Include citations with pin cites if provided; flag uncertain citations with `[VERIFY]`.

| Issue | Statute / Rule | Leading cases | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
|  |  |  |  |

**6) Evidence & Exhibits (table)**

| Exhibit ID | Description | Authenticity status | Relevance to issue | Sponsor witness |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
|  |  |  |  |  |

**7) Witnesses (table)**

| Witness | Role | Expected testimony | Prior statements | Cross targets | Impeachment |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
|  |  |  |  |  |  |

**8) Evidentiary / Procedural Flags (checklist)**  
List only what is relevant.

- Foundation / authentication gaps to cure.
- Hearsay risks and available exceptions.
- Motions in limine status and rulings.
- Objections likely from each side.
- Expert admissibility issues (methodology, qualifications, relevance).

**9) Strategy & Risk (table)**

| Strengths | Weaknesses | Opponent likely themes | Recommended responses | Settlement / stipulation leverage |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
|  |  |  |  |  |

**10) Hearing Logistics & Deadlines (checklist)**

- Briefing or exhibit exchange deadlines.
- Required filings (trial brief, witness list, exhibit list, proposed order).
- Tech needs (presentation, video, remote witness).
- Courtroom procedures (local rules, standing orders).
- Interpreter or accessibility needs.

**11) Examination Outlines (template)**  
Provide only if testimony is expected.

```
Witness: [Name]
Purpose: [Theme + issue]
Direct:
- Topic 1: [Q objectives]
- Topic 2: [Q objectives]
Cross:
- Topic 1: [Impeachment / concession]
- Topic 2: [Contradiction / bias]
```

**12) Open Items / To-Do (list)**  
Actionable items with owner and due date if known.

## Guidelines

- Use source citations for every factual assertion and quote.
- Separate facts from arguments; label advocacy explicitly.
- Do not assume law or local rules; verify and mark uncertainties with `[VERIFY]`.
- Prefer tables and checklists over narrative.
- Keep to the hearing scope; omit unrelated case history.
- Note jurisdiction and forum at the top; adjust standards accordingly.
